{
  "What was the significance of the 1972 Stockholm Conference?": "",
  "It was the last UN conference on the environment": "",
  "It focused exclusively on climate change mitigation": "",
  "It created binding pollution limits for all nations": "",
  "It was the first major UN conference focused on the human environment and led to the creation of UNEP": "",
  "The 1972 Stockholm Conference was the first major international gathering dedicated to the human environment and resulted in the establishment of the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).": "",
  "What is the primary role of the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)?": "",
  "To enforce environmental laws in every country": "",
  "To replace national environmental agencies": "",
  "To exclusively study climate change impacts": "",
  "To coordinate international environmental action, provide scientific guidance, and support environmental programs": "",
  "UNEP serves as a coordinating body for international environmental efforts, providing scientific guidance and supporting programs rather than directly enforcing laws.": "",
  "What does CITES regulate?": "",
  "Chemical weapons production and transport": "",
  "Domestic fishing quotas": "",
  "All forms of international commerce": "",
  "International trade in endangered species of wild animals and plants through a permit system": "",
  "CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species) controls international wildlife trade by requiring permits to ensure that trade does not threaten species survival.": "",
  "Why is the Montreal Protocol considered the most successful international environmental treaty?": "",
  "CFC production dropped over 99%, and the ozone layer is on track to recover by approximately 2065": "",
  "It was never challenged by industry groups": "",
  "It only required participation from five countries": "",
  "It eliminated all greenhouse gas emissions globally": "",
  "The Montreal Protocol achieved over 99% reduction in CFC production with universal ratification, and scientific evidence confirms that the ozone layer is recovering on schedule.": "",
  "What are the three objectives of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD)?": "",
  "Reduce carbon emissions, protect waterways, and eliminate invasive species": "",
  "Protect only forest ecosystems, ban all hunting, and establish parks on every continent": "",
  "Conserve biodiversity, promote sustainable use of its components, and ensure fair sharing of benefits from genetic resources": "",
  "Create species lists, fund conservation agencies, and develop wildlife corridors": "",
  "The CBD, adopted in 1992, has three interrelated objectives: conservation of biological diversity, sustainable use of its components, and fair and equitable sharing of benefits arising from genetic resources.": "",
  "What is the 30 by 30 target from the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework (2022)?": "",
  "Reduce pollution levels by 30% in 30 major cities": "",
  "Protect 30% of Earth's land and 30% of ocean areas by 2030": "",
  "Increase global forest cover by 30% within 30 years": "",
  "Reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 30% by 2030": "",
  "The 30 by 30 target aims to protect at least 30% of Earth's terrestrial and marine areas by 2030, a significant increase from current protection levels.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of land and ocean is currently under environmental protection?": "",
  "About 17% of land and 8% of ocean": "",
  "About 5% of land and 1% of ocean": "",
  "About 30% of land and 30% of ocean": "",
  "About 50% of land and 50% of ocean": "",
  "Currently, approximately 17% of land and 8% of ocean areas are protected, showing that reaching the 30 by 30 target will require nearly doubling land protection and quadrupling ocean protection.": "",
  "What does the Basel Convention (1989) regulate?": "",
  "Transboundary movement of hazardous wastes, particularly preventing dumping in developing countries": "",
  "International air pollution standards and monitoring": "",
  "Nuclear waste storage and disposal within individual countries": "",
  "Exporting endangered species to foreign zoos": "",
  "The Basel Convention controls the transboundary movement and disposal of hazardous wastes, primarily to prevent wealthy nations from exporting toxic waste to developing countries.": "",
  "What principle does the Rotterdam Convention require for trade in hazardous chemicals?": "",
  "Mandatory testing by the exporting country only": "",
  "Prior Informed Consent, meaning importing countries must agree before receiving hazardous chemicals": "",
  "No special requirements beyond standard trade rules": "",
  "Only labeling requirements for hazardous chemicals": "",
  "The Rotterdam Convention uses the Prior Informed Consent (PIC) procedure, requiring that importing countries be notified and must consent before hazardous chemicals or pesticides are shipped to them.": "",
  "What does the Stockholm Convention (2001) target?": "",
  "Only heavy metal contamination in waterways": "",
  "Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs), banning or restricting the 'dirty dozen' and other toxic chemicals": "",
  "Deforestation in tropical regions exclusively": "",
  "Carbon dioxide emissions from power plants": "",
  "The Stockholm Convention aims to eliminate or restrict the production and use of Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs), starting with an initial list of 12 chemicals known as the 'dirty dozen' and expanding to include additional toxic substances.": "",
  "What is a Multilateral Environmental Agreement (MEA)?": "",
  "A trade deal that includes environmental provisions": "",
  "A legally binding agreement between three or more nations to address shared environmental problems": "",
  "A voluntary pledge by a single nation to improve its own environment": "",
  "A scientific report published by the United Nations": "",
  "A Multilateral Environmental Agreement is a binding treaty among multiple nations that establishes commitments and mechanisms for addressing transboundary or global environmental issues.": "",
  "What is the tragedy of the commons?": "",
  "The loss of common bird species due to habitat destruction": "",
  "A political conflict between rural and urban communities over land use": "",
  "The decline of public parks in major cities": "",
  "A situation in which shared resources are overexploited because no single user bears the full cost of degradation": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons describes how individuals, acting in their own self-interest, deplete shared resources (like fisheries, the atmosphere, or oceans) because the costs are distributed among all users.": "",
  "What is the free-rider problem in international environmental treaties?": "",
  "Countries that benefit from others' environmental efforts without contributing their own fair share": "",
  "Countries that have no environmental regulations at all": "",
  "Countries that refuse to participate in any international meetings": "",
  "Countries that provide free public transportation to reduce emissions": "",
  "The free-rider problem occurs when some nations enjoy the benefits of environmental improvements achieved by others' costly efforts while avoiding those costs themselves, which undermines collective action.": "",
  "What is the precautionary principle?": "",
  "The principle that where there are threats of serious damage, lack of full scientific certainty should not postpone cost-effective preventive measures": "",
  "The concept that future generations will develop technology to fix environmental problems": "",
  "The idea that environmental action should wait until there is absolute scientific certainty": "",
  "The rule that only proven environmental dangers should be addressed": "",
  "The precautionary principle holds that when an activity poses a threat of serious or irreversible harm, protective action should be taken even if the scientific evidence is not yet complete.": "",
  "What is a debt-for-nature swap?": "",
  "A payment made by wealthy countries to poor countries for causing pollution": "",
  "An exchange of natural resources between two countries to settle trade disputes": "",
  "A program in which a developing country's foreign debt is reduced in exchange for investments in domestic conservation programs": "",
  "A loan given to developing countries to build national parks": "",
  "Debt-for-nature swaps are creative financial mechanisms in which a portion of a developing nation's foreign debt is forgiven in return for commitments to invest in domestic environmental conservation.": "",
  "What is national sovereignty in the context of international environmental policy?": "",
  "A nation's authority over its own territory and resources, which may lead to resistance against binding international environmental commitments": "",
  "The principle that wealthy nations should control global environmental policy": "",
  "The requirement that all nations vote unanimously on environmental treaties": "",
  "The idea that every nation should have its own environmental agency": "",
  "National sovereignty refers to a country's right to govern itself without external interference, which creates a fundamental challenge for international environmental treaties that require nations to accept binding limits on their activities.": "",
  "What is a pollution haven?": "",
  "A nature reserve that is protected from all forms of pollution": "",
  "A country or region with weak environmental regulations that attracts polluting industries seeking to avoid stricter rules elsewhere": "",
  "A region designated for storing hazardous materials safely": "",
  "An area where pollution levels naturally decrease over time": "",
  "Pollution havens are jurisdictions with lax environmental regulations that attract polluting industries relocating from countries with stricter standards, illustrating how trade and environmental policy intersect.": "",
  "What is South-South cooperation in environmental policy?": "",
  "Environmental partnerships between countries in the Southern Hemisphere and Antarctica": "",
  "Competition among developing nations for environmental funding": "",
  "Aid flowing from developed to developing nations for environmental projects": "",
  "Developing countries sharing knowledge, technology, and strategies with each other to address environmental challenges": "",
  "South-South cooperation involves developing nations collaborating with each other to share environmental knowledge, technologies, and strategies, recognizing that they face similar challenges.": "",
  "What is the Persistent Organic Pollutant (POP) known as the 'dirty dozen'?": "",
  "The initial list of twelve highly toxic chemicals targeted for elimination by the Stockholm Convention": "",
  "The twelve most common greenhouse gases": "",
  "The twelve most polluted rivers in the world": "",
  "The twelve countries that produce the most pollution": "",
  "The 'dirty dozen' refers to the original twelve persistent organic pollutants targeted by the Stockholm Convention, including DDT, PCBs, dioxins, and furans, which are highly toxic, persist in the environment, and bioaccumulate.": "",
  "What is the Multilateral Fund associated with the Montreal Protocol?": "",
  "A fund that pays fines for countries that violate the treaty": "",
  "A savings account for future environmental emergencies": "",
  "A financial mechanism that helps developing countries cover the costs of phasing out ozone-depleting substances": "",
  "A research fund for discovering new chemicals to replace all plastics": "",
  "The Multilateral Fund was established under the Montreal Protocol to provide financial and technical assistance to developing countries, helping them transition away from ozone-depleting substances, which was key to the treaty's universal participation.": "",
  "A coastal nation discovers that large quantities of electronic waste from developed countries are being shipped to its ports and dismantled in informal settings, exposing workers and communities to toxic heavy metals. Which international agreement is most directly relevant to addressing this situation?": "",
  "The Basel Convention": "",
  "The Montreal Protocol": "",
  "The Convention on Biological Diversity": "",
  "CITES": "",
  "The Basel Convention specifically regulates the transboundary movement of hazardous wastes, including electronic waste, and aims to prevent developed countries from dumping toxic materials in developing nations.": "",
  "Two neighboring countries share a major fishery in international waters. Fish populations have been declining for years as both nations increase their catches. Neither country is willing to reduce its fleet unilaterally because fishers from the other country would simply catch more. This situation best illustrates which concept?": "",
  "A debt-for-nature swap opportunity": "",
  "The precautionary principle": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons": "",
  "The pollution haven hypothesis": "",
  "This is a classic tragedy of the commons scenario: a shared resource (the fishery) is being overexploited because each nation has an incentive to maximize its own catch while the costs of depletion are shared by all.": "",
  "A developing country with high foreign debt and significant tropical rainforest coverage is approached by an international conservation organization. The organization offers to purchase a portion of the debt at a discount in exchange for the country investing in rainforest conservation. What type of mechanism is being proposed?": "",
  "A debt-for-nature swap": "",
  "A carbon offset program": "",
  "A CITES permit exemption": "",
  "A cap-and-trade carbon market": "",
  "This describes a debt-for-nature swap, a creative conservation finance tool where a portion of a developing country's foreign debt is reduced in exchange for commitments to fund domestic environmental conservation.": "",
  "Country A has strict environmental regulations for chemical manufacturing, while Country B has very few. A large chemical company moves its most polluting operations from Country A to Country B. Meanwhile, a new pesticide banned in Country A is being exported to Country B without informing the government. Which two concepts are illustrated here?": "",
  "CITES violations and Basel Convention breaches": "",
  "South-South cooperation and the precautionary principle": "",
